This is what I was going to point out. Ant has properties that you can set to omit certain, classes, suites, tests, etc... I use the same method that Erik does, but it is actually in my build script using ant. Looks like this:

 &lt;target name=&quot;compile-test&quot; depends=&quot;prepare,load-project&quot;&gt;
      &lt;echo message=&quot;Compiling project ${proj.name} tests...&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;javac srcdir=&quot;${test.java.dir}&quot;
             destdir=&quot;${build.dir}/test&quot;
      debug=&quot;on&quot;
             includes=&quot;${proj.package}/**/*.java&quot;
             excludes=&quot;${proj.compile.excludes}&quot; &gt;             
         &lt;classpath refid=&quot;project.class.path&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/javac&gt;
   &lt;/target&gt;

Michael Orozco

Hope this helps?!

Paul Christmann &lt;java-junit@...&gt; wrote:
Use the errorProperty/failureProperty attributes of the &lt;junit&gt; task 
instead:


     &lt;junit printsummary=&quot;true&quot;
              showoutput=&quot;${junit.showoutput}&quot;
           errorProperty=&quot;junit.failed&quot;
         failureProperty=&quot;junit.failed&quot;
                     dir=&quot;${unittest.classes.dir}&quot;
                    fork=&quot;yes&quot;&gt;
       &lt;!-- Stuff omitted --&gt;
     &lt;/junit&gt;

     &lt;junitreport todir=&quot;${junit.reports}&quot;&gt;
       &lt;!-- Stuff omitted --&gt;
     &lt;/junitreport&gt;

     &lt;fail message=&quot;Test Cases Failed&quot; if=&quot;junit.failed&quot;/&gt;

